# ── FRED HAMPTON ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
make(
  filename='/home/user/app/thread-fred-hampton.html',
  acc=acc, acc_lt=acc_lt, hero_bg=hero_bg,
  kicker='Civil Rights → Backlash · 1948 – 1969',
  title_html='Fred Hampton:<br /><em>The Chairman They Killed at 21</em>',
  subtitle="Fred Hampton became chairman of the Illinois Black Panther Party at 20. He built a coalition across gang lines, organized a breakfast program feeding thousands of children, and united Chicago's most dangerous rival gangs into a political force. On December 4, 1969, the FBI and Chicago police shot him dead in his bed at 4:45 a.m. He was 21.",
  meta_items=[('Era','Civil Rights → Backlash'),('Born','August 30, 1948, Summit, Illinois'),('Died','December 4, 1969, Chicago — murdered by Chicago PD/FBI'),('Known for','Rainbow Coalition, Illinois BPP, assassination at 21')],
  central_arg="Fred Hampton's assassination is not a historical controversy. It is a documented fact: the FBI's COINTELPRO program identified Hampton as a rising leader, planted informants in his organization, provided a floor plan of his apartment to Chicago police, and coordinated the raid in which he was shot in his bed while sedated. The government killed him because he was building a multi-racial, multi-gang coalition that they believed was more dangerous than any individual radical.",
  entries_html="""
<div class="entry-item" id="e1">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">1</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">1948 – 1968</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">The Organizer: From the NAACP Youth Council to the Panthers</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Maywood, Illinois → Chicago</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>Fred Hampton grows up in Maywood, a suburb of Chicago, where he becomes president of the NAACP Youth Council at 16 — organizing campaigns for equal access to a public swimming pool and a local park that excluded Black children. He is a natural organizer: charismatic, analytically sharp, and capable of making complex political arguments accessible to anyone. When the Black Panther Party reaches Chicago in 1968, he joins and rises quickly. At 20, he becomes chairman of the <strong>Illinois Black Panther Party</strong>.</p>
    <p>His analysis differs from some Panther chapters in its explicit focus on class as well as race. He builds alliances with poor white groups — including the <strong>Young Patriots Organization</strong>, a Southern working-class white group in Chicago — and with Puerto Rican groups including the <strong>Young Lords</strong>. He calls this coalition-building his "<strong>Rainbow Coalition</strong>" — a term later taken by Jesse Jackson. His argument: poor people of all races have more in common with each other than with the wealthy people of any race who exploit them.</p>
    <div class="entry-stats">
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">21</div><div class="entry-stat__label">Age at assassination</div></div>
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">1969</div><div class="entry-stat__label">Year FBI/Chicago PD killed him</div></div>
      <div><div class="entry-stat__num">$1.85M</div><div class="entry-stat__label">Settlement paid to Hampton's family, 1982</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="entry-item" id="e2">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">2</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">1969</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">The Rainbow Coalition: Uniting Gangs, Poor Whites, and Puerto Ricans</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">Chicago</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>Hampton's most remarkable achievement is the <strong>truce he negotiates between Chicago's rival street gangs</strong> — the Blackstone Rangers and the Disciples — and his incorporation of gang members into political organizing. He sees gang members not as criminals but as mis-directed community power: young men with organizational capacity and territorial loyalty who lack political direction. He gives them direction. The gangs begin running Free Breakfast Programs. They begin attending political education classes. The FBI is alarmed.</p>
    <p>The Rainbow Coalition at its peak includes the Illinois Black Panther Party, the Young Patriots (poor white Appalachian migrants), the Young Lords (Puerto Rican), the Brown Berets (Mexican-American), the American Indian Movement, and reformed gang members from the Rangers and Disciples. Hampton is building the kind of cross-racial, cross-gang political coalition that the Chicago machine — and the FBI — found genuinely threatening. An FBI memo from this period identifies Hampton as a potential "<strong>Black Messiah</strong>" who could unify radical movements across racial lines.</p>
    <div class="pullquote"><p>"You fight racism with solidarity. I don't fight racism with racism. I'm gonna fight racism with solidarity."</p><cite>— Fred Hampton, 1969</cite></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="entry-item" id="e3">
  <div class="entry-item__header"><div class="entry-item__num">3</div>
  <div><div class="entry-item__dates">December 4, 1969</div>
  <h2 class="entry-item__name">The Assassination: What COINTELPRO and Chicago Police Did</h2>
  <div class="entry-item__location">2337 West Monroe Street, Chicago</div></div></div>
  <div class="entry-item__body">
    <p>At 4:45 a.m. on December 4, 1969, a 14-person Chicago Police Department tactical unit — coordinated with the FBI and armed with a floor plan of Hampton's apartment provided by FBI informant <strong>William O'Neal</strong> (Hampton's own security chief) — raids the apartment. Hampton is in bed with his pregnant girlfriend, <strong>Deborah Johnson</strong>. He has been drugged: the FBI had arranged for O'Neal to spike his drinks with secobarbital the previous evening, and an autopsy finds a near-lethal dose in his system.</p>
    <p>The initial police account: they were ambushed by Panther gunfire. Physical evidence showed otherwise. <strong>Evidence technicians found 99 bullets fired into the apartment from outside — and one, possibly two, fired from inside</strong>. Hampton never regained consciousness during the raid. According to Deborah Johnson, two officers entered the bedroom after the initial shooting. She heard one say, "He's still alive." Then two shots. Then: "He's good and dead now." Hampton is shot twice in the head at point-blank range.</p>
    <p>The federal government pays Hampton's family <strong>$1.85 million</strong> in 1982 — an implicit acknowledgment of wrongful death. No officer is ever criminally charged. The FBI's COINTELPRO program, which orchestrated Hampton's killing, is formally ended in 1971 after its documents are stolen by activists and published. It had been running since 1956.</p>
  </div>
</div>
""",
  sidebar_html="""<div class="sidebar-card"><div class="sidebar-card__title">COINTELPRO's Role</div><div class="sidebar-card__body">The FBI's counterintelligence program designated Hampton a "Black Nationalist Hate Group" leader and "potential threat." Actions taken:<br/><br/>• Planted informant William O'Neal as Hampton's security chief<br/>• O'Neal provided floor plan of Hampton's apartment to Chicago PD<br/>• O'Neal drugged Hampton the night before the raid<br/>• FBI coordinated with Chicago PD raid planning<br/><br/>No federal agent was ever charged.</div></div>
<div class="sidebar-card"><div class="sidebar-card__title">The Legacy</div><div class="sidebar-card__body">Jesse Jackson adopted Hampton's "Rainbow Coalition" name for his 1984 presidential campaign<br/><br/>The Free Breakfast Program Hampton organized became the model for the national school breakfast program<br/><br/>The 2021 film <em>Judas and the Black Messiah</em> dramatizes Hampton's assassination and O'Neal's role</div></div>""",
  cta_eyebrow='Killed at 21 by the Government He Organized Against',
  cta_title='The FBI planted his security chief as an informant, drugged him, and gave police the floor plan of his bedroom.',
  cta_sub='Hampton wasn\'t killed because he was violent. He was killed because he was building a multi-racial coalition across gang lines that the FBI identified as the most dangerous kind of organizing in America.',
  cta_href='thread-cointelpro.html', cta_text='COINTELPRO →', context_era='Civil Rights'
)
